{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-84c0b6484ac86e46", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tTowards a reproducible cross-venue method for\n2\tquantifying crowd noise in stadiums\n3\tAlejandro Osses, Bente Ackermans, Helmer Nuijens, Rick Scholte\n4\tSorama BV, Eindhoven, the Netherlands\n5\t\n6\tarXiv:2607.18922v1 [eess.AS] 21 Jul 2026\n7\t\n8\talejandro.osses@sorama.eu,\n9\t\n10\tAbstract\n11\tPublic claims about the “loudest stadium” have been\n12\tbased on an instantaneous peak dB(A) reading measured at a single point, as popularised by the Guinness\n13\tWorld Records “loudest crowd roar” category. The current record dates from 2014, where a maximum level of\n14\t142.2 dB(A) was registered. While compelling, those\n15\tmeasurements lack standardisation, omitting relevant information such as the specific instrument that was used,\n16\tthe usage of time weighting, and the number of measurement positions that were tested. This lack of information does not allow a well-founded scientific comparison across sport venues. This study proposes a measurement framework in which spatially distributed acoustic\n17\tmeasurement is the recommended route for a representative cross-venue comparison, while a single-anchor measurement can only serve as a minimum reporting baseline\n18\twhen distributed measurements are not feasible.\n19\t\n20\t1. Introduction\n21\tSport venues with passionate supporters are\n22\trenowned for their lively and engaging atmosphere,\n23\tin which sound plays a central role. The acoustic\n24\tenvironment in a stadium is not just a by-product of\n25\tspectatorship, but it is rather an active contributor to\n26\tthe dynamics of the game [1]. In particular, players\n27\ton the pitch are influenced —both positively and\n28\tnegatively— by the presence of crowd noise [2].\n29\tElevated sound levels can enhance motivation and\n30\tperceived home advantage, while at the same time\n31\t\n32\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n33\t\n34\tinfo@sorama.eu\n35\t\n36\tinterfere with communication, concentration, and\n37\tdecision making [3–5]. As such, the notion of a\n38\t“loud stadium” is inherently tied to how sound is\n39\tperceived by players during a game.\n40\tBeyond its impact on players, sound in stadiums has additional roles. It contributes to the overall\n41\tspectator experience, reinforces collective engagement among supporters, and influences how events\n42\tare perceived through broadcast media. These multiple roles make sound a key parameter in the evaluation of stadium atmosphere. Despite this, the quantification of “crowd noise” is typically focused on\n43\tsimplified metrics, often detached from the actual experience on the pitch.\n44\tMany crowd noise records exist and are often reported in press articles or compiled by organisations\n45\tsuch as Guinness World Records (GWR), as summarised in Table 1.\n46\tThe current loudest venue was registered in 2014\n47\tat Arrowhead stadium during an American football\n48\tmatch [6]. The record was obtained as a peak reading from a sound level meter providing a level of\n49\t142.2 dB(A). It is unclear which specific instrument\n50\twas used, where it was located, and how this reading compares to the history of levels across different\n51\tmeasurement positions, matches, and seasons. These\n52\tobservations are also valid for the other venues that\n53\tare listed in Table 1.\n54\tWhile peak values are straightforward to com-\n55\t\n56\tPage 1\n57\t\n58\t\fTable 1: List of loudest stadiums with a reported acoustic level. Most of these levels have been reported in A-weighted dB values,\n59\tdB(A), however, when not explicitly mentioned, the unit is marked as “dB.”\n60\tDate\n61\tSep 29, 2014\n62\tDec 2, 2013\n63\tOct 13, 2013\n64\tNov 8, 2023\n65\tSep 15, 2013\n66\tSep 19, 1999\n67\t2007\n68\tMar 18, 2011\n69\tNot reported\n70\tFeb 13, 2017\n71\tNov 5, 2024\n72\tAug 24, 2025\n73\tOct 15, 2022\n74\t\n75\tHome team\n76\tKansas City Chiefs\n77\tSeattle Seahawks\n78\tKansas City Chiefs\n79\tTennessee\n80\tSeattle Seahawks\n81\tUniversity of Washington\n82\tBeşiktaş\n83\tGalatasaray\n84\tFenerbahçe\n85\tKansas Jayhawks\n86\tCeltic\n87\tEverton FC\n88\tTennessee\n89\t\n90\tVenue\n91\tArrowhead stadium\n92\tLumen field\n93\tArrowhead stadium\n94\tNeyland stadium\n95\tLumen field\n96\tHusky stadium\n97\tVodafone Park\n98\tAli Sami Yen stadium\n99\tŞükrü Saracoğlu stadium\n100\tAllen Fieldhouse\n101\tCeltic Park\n102\tHill Dickinson stadium\n103\tNeyland stadium\n104\t\n105\tmunicate, they are limited from a scientific perspective. In particular, such values do not ensure\n106\trepresentativity or reproducibility across venues and\n107\tevents [16]. This limitation is particularly relevant\n108\twhen the quantity of interest is the sound as experienced by players, rather than the maximum level at a\n109\tsingle measurement location. Several limitations that\n110\tare associated with current practices are:\n111\t• The use of a peak reading is not aligned with standard acoustic procedures because transient or other\n112\textraneous sounds are typically not representative\n113\tof the sound sources under investigation [17, 18].\n114\tActually, transient sounds —as those that can be\n115\tpicked up by a peak reading— often require a separate treatment [19].\n116\t• If instead of a peak reading, the estimate of maximum levels is based on fast-integrated sound pressure levels, the estimations will be lowered by at\n117\tleast 10 dB [16], a non-negligible difference. This\n118\tdifference is illustrated later in Figure 2.\n119\t• The measurement position seems to be chosen\n120\tbased on intuition rather than using any spatial or\n121\tacoustic criterion. Employing an acoustic criterion\n122\tcould ensure, for example, that the measurements\n123\tare collected in the stable acoustic far field.\n124\t• Because there is no spatial criterion to choose the\n125\tmeasurement locations, there is no guarantee that\n126\tthe highest crowd levels are being registered.\n127\t\n128\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n129\t\n130\tCity\n131\tKansas City, USA\n132\tSeattle, USA\n133\tKansas City, USA\n134\tKnoxville, USA\n135\tSeattle, USA\n136\tSeattle, USA\n137\tIstanbul, Turkey\n138\tIstanbul, Turkey\n139\tIstanbul, Turkey\n140\tLawrence, Kansas, USA\n141\tGlasgow, Scotland\n142\tLiverpool, UK\n143\tKnoxville, USA\n144\t\n145\tSport\n146\tAmerican football\n147\tAmerican football\n148\tAmerican football\n149\tAmerican football\n150\tAmerican football\n151\tAmerican football\n152\tFootball\n153\tFootball\n154\tFootball\n155\tBasketball\n156\tFootball\n157\tFootball\n158\tAmerican football\n159\t\n160\tLevel\n161\t142.2 dB(A)\n162\t137.6 dB(A)\n163\t137.5 dB\n164\t137.0 dB\n165\t136.6 dB\n166\t133.6 dB\n167\t132.0 dB\n168\t131.76 dB(A)\n169\t131.0 dB\n170\t130.4 dB(A)\n171\t129.0 dB\n172\t126.0 dB\n173\t125.4 dB\n174\t\n175\tSource\n176\t[6]\n177\t[7]\n178\t[8]\n179\t[9]\n180\t[10]\n181\t[11]\n182\t[12]\n183\t[13]\n184\t[12]\n185\t[14]\n186\t[12]\n187\t[12]\n188\t[15]\n189\t\n190\tIn other words, the current practices can lead to\n191\tnon-representative results or even to invalid acoustic\n192\tmeasurements. The goal of this study is to establish the foundations of a more rigorous measurement\n193\tprotocol, so that the reliability of future crowd-noise\n194\testimates is increased. The adoption of such a protocol will also allow to (1) characterise the crowd\n195\tbehaviour during specific match actions, making a\n196\tdistinction of the supporters’ behaviour during, e.g.,\n197\ta goal or a free throw [4]; (2) assess noise exposure\n198\tmetrics [20,21] as typically evaluated in hearing conservation programs of noise at work [22]; (3) project\n199\tthe estimates to predict exterior sound pressure levels, outside the stadium (e.g., [4]).\n200\tIn this study we introduce a method to assess\n201\tcrowd levels at stadiums using one or multiple acoustic measurement devices. The method can use single microphone devices, such as sound level meters,\n202\tbut can also use distributed microphone arrays, also\n203\tknown as acoustic cameras. The structure of this paper is as follows: We start by identifying the limitations of the current crowd noise estimate (Section 2) and defining the criteria that must be fulfilled to ensure its reliable and representative quantification (Section 3). Based on those requirements,\n204\twe first define a representative stadium crowd level\n205\tand then describe a measurement framework (Section 4) in which spatially distributed measurements\n206\tare the preferred implementation for a cross-venue\n207\tcomparison. We focus on practical and technical as-\n208\t\n209\tPage 2\n210\t\n211\t\fpects that can lead to an objective and scalable noise\n212\tmonitoring system in indoor, semi-open, and outdoor sport venues. Finally we emphasise the scope\n213\tof the method and indicate the limitations of the current proposal with an eye on future extensions of the\n214\tmethod.\n215\t\n216\t(a) Current device positioning as used in the GWR procedure.\n217\t\n218\t2. Loudest crowd roar: Current practice\n219\tDespite the omission of specific technical details in\n220\tthe GWR procedure, in the category “loudest crowd\n221\troar at a sports stadium,” the method has been systematically used in the last decades [6–11, 14]. The\n222\t“loudest crowd roar” or, better said, the highest\n223\tcrowd noise level 1 was claimed to be a peak dB(A)\n224\treading during a specific match moment. From press\n225\tresources (see, e.g., pictures from [6,10]) can be seen\n226\tthat the metric has been based on point measurements collected with a Class 1 sound level meter Larson Davis 831, which was located very close to the\n227\tcrowd. A schematic stadium illustrating the positioning of such a single measurement device is depicted\n228\tin Figure 1(a).\n229\tThe GWR approach disregards the impact of the\n230\tcrowd on the pitch and it does not give the possibility to supporters in other audience areas to become\n231\tthe loudest fans. These drawbacks can be partly mitigated if the measurement device is targeted to the\n232\tpitch, as depicted in Figure 1(b). We will come back\n233\tto this discussion later, when multiple-device systems are introduced.\n234\t2.1 Why is a peak dB(A) reading ambiguous?\n235\tPeak levels are not typically used in environmental\n236\tnor architectural acoustic standards. The main reason is that acoustic metrics have been developed to\n237\taccount for relevant aspects of human sound perception. One of these aspects is the difficulty of our ears\n238\t1\n239\t\n240\tDespite the fact that the term loudness or loudest crowd has\n241\tbeen widely used, we will refrain as much as possible from its\n242\tuse. The reason is that loudness is actually the perceptual counterpart of sound pressure levels, expressed in Sones and not in\n243\tdB as it is the case for sound levels [23, 24]. We will instead\n244\trefer to “crowd noise estimates” or “crowd levels.”\n245\t\n246\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n247\t\n248\t(b) One-device system that is pointed to the middle of the pitch.\n249\tThis arbitrary point will capture sounds coming from multiple\n250\taudience sections.\n251\t\n252\tFigure 1: Generic stadium showing the pitch (in green) and audience areas (in grey), using one measurement device (microphone symbol). Panel (a) reflects the device positioning as it\n253\thas been so far used for crowd noise measurements, targeting a\n254\tspecific audience area, which is assumed to produce the highest\n255\tcrowd-noise levels. Two drawbacks of the current approach are:\n256\t(1) supporters in other sections do not get the possibility to become the loudest fans, because there is no measurement device\n257\tin their neighbourhood, and (2) the impact of the crowd onto\n258\tthe pitch, where the players are performing, is unknown. The\n259\tone-device set-up shown in Panel (b) partly copes with those\n260\tlimitations as it is pointed to the pitch which, by design, receives\n261\tthe level contribution from all the audience areas.\n262\t\n263\tto react to transient sounds. The ear is a “sluggish”\n264\torgan that requires a time of about 200 ms to react\n265\tto sudden level changes (see [25], p. 64), resulting in\n266\tsounds that are perceived as a slower and smoother\n267\ttime-varying envelope, despite the strongly-varying\n268\ttime information contained in a sound waveform.\n269\tHistorically, time weightings were adopted for tracking changes in level by a sound level meter due to\n270\tearly physical limitations of the old analog volume\n271\tunit (VU) meters. Many years after, the fast integration time constant of 125 ms is well accepted as\n272\ta correlate to the slower-varying perceived envelope\n273\tand it is widely recommended in multiple international standards. According to ISO 1996-1 [17] that\n274\tdefines basic quantities used in environmental acoustics, two suitable metrics to characterise sound events\n275\t\n276\tPage 3\n277\t\n278\t\fare the fast-integrated maximum level LAF,max and\n279\tcontinuous equivalent level LAeq . The subindex “A”\n280\tindicates the use of the A-weighting curve, whose\n281\tuse is another add-on to the level assessments that\n282\thas been inspired by perceptual aspects, reflecting\n283\tthe ear’s frequency-dependent sensitivity [26].\n284\tConsidering all these arguments, a peak reading\n285\tdoes not consider the time required to integrate a\n286\tsound, and therefore is not a suitable measure of perceived amplitudes. In fact, the exclusion of transient\n287\tsounds is a common acoustic practice (e.g., [18]).\n288\tMore generally, a peak reading can be seen as an\n289\testimator of a maximum value in a waveform. The\n290\twaveform of a goal moment is shown in light blue\n291\t\n292\tin Figure 2(a) and its peak maximum is indicated\n293\tby a blue square marker. The adoption of a fast\n294\ttime weighting will naturally smooth the waveform,\n295\tconverting it into a much slower time varying envelope (thick pink trace). The fast-integrated maximum in panel (a) (pink circle marker) is 3.8 times\n296\tsmaller than the peak maximum reading. The maximum estimates and the envelope are expressed in\n297\tdB in panel (b), emphasising that for this example\n298\tthe peak reading overestimates the maximum level\n299\tby 11.6 dB.\n300\tAnother important aspect is that the measuring\n301\tdevice will only be able to capture sounds that are under its microphone acoustic overload point. Acoustic overload points represent the maximum physical\n302\tlevel of a measuring device before saturating, and\n303\tare reported in dB(Z), i.e., before any time or frequency weighting is applied. Typical overload points\n304\tare between 130 and 150 dB(Z). The reported overload point for the Larson Davis 831 sound level meter is 143 dB(Z) [27], which is suspiciously close to\n305\tthe reported 142.2 dB(A). This could mean that the\n306\tGWR measurement might have been pushed down\n307\tby the saturation point of the measurement device.\n308\t2.2 Focus on the audience, the players, or both?\n309\t\n310\tFigure 2: Goal moment for a football match between PSV Eindhoven and RKC Waalwijk on 19 May 2024 from the Dutch Eredivisie. Ten seconds around the exact goal moment are drawn.\n311\tPanel (a) shows a waveform (in light blue) measured by an\n312\tNTi XL2 Class 1 sound level meter which has a maximum of\n313\t24.4 Pascals or 121.7 dB (blue square marker). The pink trace\n314\tshows the temporal envelope after the waveform was subjected\n315\tto a fast time integration. The maximum of that curve is 6.4 Pascals or 110.1 dB (pink circle marker). Panel (b) shows the envelope and the maximum estimates expressed in dB. The difference\n316\tbetween the maximum level estimated from the peak reading and\n317\tfrom the fast-integrated levels is 11.6 dB (reduction by a factor\n318\tof 3.8).\n319\t\n320\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n321\t\n322\tSo far, crowd noise estimates have been focused on\n323\tsounds produced by the audience. This is probably\n324\tthe most straightforward way to estimate the supporters’ strength and commitment to the team they support. We must not forget, however, that the supporters are primarily driven by the active players on the\n325\tpitch and their actions (e.g., [4]). If players can have\n326\tsuch a direct impact on the supporters, why are the\n327\tcrowd noise estimates not focused on sound levels as\n328\tprojected onto the players?\n329\tA well-known case of the negative impact of\n330\tcrowd noise on a player was reported in 2017 during\n331\ta football match between Beşiktaş and RB Leipzig\n332\tat the Vodafone stadium (ranked 7th in Table 1) valid\n333\tfor the UEFA Champions League [28]. During the\n334\tgame, the German player Timo Werner (RB Leipzig)\n335\trequested the use of ear plugs and finally left the\n336\t\n337\tPage 4\n338\t\n339\t\fpitch after suffering from circulation problems as a\n340\tconsequence of the loud perception of the Beşiktaş’\n341\tsupporter roars.\n342\tFocusing on sounds on the pitch seems to be a\n343\tstrategic choice because the reference measurement\n344\tpoints will be confined in a smaller area with known\n345\tdimensions, facilitating the comparison across stadiums. A schematic example of a straightforward\n346\tpoint to spot on the pitch, the middle point of the\n347\tvenue, is illustrated in Figure 1(b). What needs to\n348\tbe investigated is whether crowd levels on the pitch\n349\twill indeed be more representative of the overall atmosphere in the stadium compared to an evaluation\n350\tpurely focused on the audience. A data-driven discussion of this issue can help identify the most effective approach.\n351\t3. Improving the crowd noise estimation\n352\t3.1 Frequencies of interest and their far field\n353\tEnvironmental and room acoustics measurements\n354\timplicitly assume that the data are collected satisfying a far field condition. The far field relates to\n355\tthe region in space where the underlying wavefronts\n356\tof the sound source can be approximated as planar\n357\twaves. The far field recommendation can be linked\n358\tto the wavelength of the lowest frequency of interest.\n359\t3.1.1 Target frequency range\n360\tFor stadiums and particularly focusing on sounds\n361\temitted by a crowd, we suggest the target frequency\n362\trange between 100 and 8000 Hz (see, e.g., Chapter 4\n363\tfrom [29]). This choice offers a pragmatic trade-off\n364\tto capture:\n365\t• Fundamental frequency f0 of loud voices (90270 Hz): For male voices the average f0 for vowels\n366\tis 120 Hz, between 80 and 180 Hz, and for female\n367\tvoices is 200 Hz, between 150 and 260 Hz. A rise\n368\tof about 10 Hz is expected for loud voices [30].\n369\t• The effective range of vocal energy\n370\t(300–3000 Hz): This range contains the formant\n371\tcomponents of vowels and voiced consonants [31].\n372\t\n373\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n374\t\n375\t• Consonant content (3000–8000 Hz) as found in\n376\tfricative consonants (e.g., “s,” “sh,” and “th”) and,\n377\tto a lesser extent in plosive consonants (e.g., “t,”\n378\t“k,” “b,” “d,” etc.) [31].\n379\t• Whistles and clapping transients as well as sharp\n380\tcheering bursts (3000–8000 Hz) (e.g., [32]).\n381\t• Chant detection (300–3000 Hz): This frequency\n382\trange allows to keep all the relevant information\n383\tto get intelligible speech (e.g., [33]).\n384\tBy focusing on measurements between 100 and\n385\t8000 Hz, very low frequency components that are\n386\tunlikely related to crowds are excluded. Although\n387\tthis filtering seems very rough, slow frequency fluctuations (<20 Hz) that are relevant for the perception\n388\tof sound reality [34, 35] are not affected. Those slow\n389\tfluctuations are well retained by the temporal envelope in the 100-8000 Hz range [34].\n390\t3.1.2 Measurement distance: Far field criterion\n391\tTo ensure a far-field measurement under the classical acoustic assumptions, the lowest target frequency\n392\t––corresponding to the longest wavelength—- must\n393\tsatisfy the far-field criterion. This wavelength represents the most restrictive condition for the validity of\n394\tthe far-field approximation.\n395\tIn this study, we adopt the simplified relation:\n396\trcritical = 2 · λ\n397\t\n398\t(1)\n399\t\n400\twhere rcritical is the minimum distance in meters between the sound source (i.e., the crowd) and the measurement position required to ensure the free-field\n401\tconditions, and λ is the wavelength in meters associated with the lowest frequency of interest. 2\n402\tA far-field measurement ensures that the measurement position lies outside both the reactive\n403\tnear-field and the transition region, where spherical\n404\t2\n405\t\n406\tEquation (1) is independent of the size of the sound source\n407\tunder investigation. Such independence \u0001derives from the Fraunhofer distance where rcritical = 2 · D2 /λ. Equation (1) will\n408\tbe obtained when the characteristic dimension D of the source\n409\tis assumed to be acoustically small, conservatively using D = λ\n410\t(more generally with D ≤ λ).\n411\t\n412\tPage 5\n413\t\n414\t\fdation is not met for the two front-most seat rows,\n415\twhich are still in near field. For the same schematic\n416\tstadium, Figure 3(b) shows a measurement position\n417\tthat meets with suggested far-field criterion.\n418\t3.2 Requirements for a cross-venue\n419\tstadium-noise metric\n420\t\n421\t(a)\n422\t\n423\tTo ensure the comparability of a crowd-noise metric\n424\tacross stadiums we suggest some criteria related to:\n425\t(1) the measurements to be conducted, and (2) the\n426\ttraceability of the instruments to be used.\n427\t3.2.1 Measurements\n428\t• Level readings (1): The measurements should be\n429\tbased on sound pressure level readings in dB(A).\n430\t\n431\t(b)\n432\t\n433\tFigure 3: Position of a measuring device —shown as a\n434\tschematic microphone— which is either (a) in front of the\n435\tstands, as it could be done if a sound level meter is used for\n436\tthe measurements, or (b) on the roof, as a fixed installation, as it\n437\tcould be done when using a weatherproof continuous monitoring microphone or a microphone array. The critical distance dcrit\n438\tis shown as the boundary between the near and far fields. The\n439\tshaded areas represent the position in space where we discourage to obtain crowd level estimates.\n440\t\n441\tspreading and stable radiation conditions can be assumed [36].\n442\tConsidering that λ = c/f low , with c being the\n443\tspeed of sound equal to ∼340 m/s in air and f low =\n444\t100 Hz being the lowest target frequency, and replacing these values in equation (1) result in a pragmatic minimum distance criterion rcritical of 6.8 m\n445\twith respect to the audience area. 3 In larger stadium\n446\tgeometries or highly reflective environments, additional validation may be required. Figure 3(a) shows\n447\ta schematic situation where the rcritical recommen3\n448\t\n449\tIf for convenience a nominal rcritical of 8 m is used, the minimum frequency of interest f low is extended down to 85 Hz.\n450\t\n451\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n452\t\n453\t• Level readings (2): The levels should use a time\n454\tintegration equal to or greater than 125 ms, as defined for a fast time weighting [37]. A slow time\n455\tweighting could also be adopted (time constant of\n456\t1 s), but longer time constants will generally be\n457\tless sensitive to sudden crowd cheers. We suggest\n458\tto adopt the standard fast time integration.\n459\t• Location (1): The measurement points should be\n460\tspatially meaningful: the exact position should be\n461\tbased on an objective criterion. The measurement\n462\tpoint should dominantly capture human-generated\n463\tsounds during the “observation period.”\n464\t• Location (2): The distance between each measurement device and the audience area should be reported. The microphone(s) of the device should\n465\tbe 1.5 m or farther from any obstructing surface\n466\tand pointed towards the audience (e.g., see section A.4 in [38]).\n467\t• Data integrity: The crowd noise estimate should\n468\tbe derived from sound levels that only contain actual crowd noise. Sounds from electronic amplification systems should be excluded from the\n469\tcrowd-level estimate where possible, or explicitly\n470\treported as separate contributions. Non-electronic\n471\tsupporter-generated instruments, such as drums,\n472\t\n473\tPage 6\n474\t\n475\t\fhorns or vuvuzelas, should be reported separately\n476\tor treated according to sport- and league-specific\n477\treporting rules.\n478\t3.2.2 Traceability of the measurements\n479\t• The measurement device should have a Class 1\n480\tlevel accuracy. We refer to “Class 1 level accuracy” devices to (1) sound level meters that comply with IEC 61672-1 [37], or (2) microphone arrays for which a frequency response measured at\n481\tan angle of 0 degrees (in front of the device), complies with the acceptance limits defined in Table 3\n482\tfrom [37]. These limits should be met for the target\n483\tfrequency range of the analyses.\n484\t• The dynamic range of operation of the instrument\n485\tshould be reported. The target maximum levels\n486\tshould be below the acoustic overload point. If\n487\tthere is a risk of saturation during the measurements, this should be explicitly stated.\n488\t\n489\t• Match statistics (2): Relevant match statistics\n490\tmight be sport related. In that case, comparisons across stadiums can be difficult because\n491\teach stadium constitutes a different source-pathreceiver system, where the source, i.e., the supporters are very different from sport to sport. It\n492\tmay thus be relevant to consider the construction\n493\tof within-sport databases, with the technical argument that the sound-source dependent transfer\n494\tfunction of a stadium varies from sport to sport [1].\n495\tMulti-purpose sport venues may then have different crowd levels when used for different sports.\n496\t3.3 Field calibration and standards alignment\n497\t• Field calibration: The measurement devices\n498\tshould be checked for field calibration before and\n499\tafter the events, so that drift logs are registered.\n500\tNext to the field calibration, meteorological information (temperature and relative humidity) is desirable to be recorded.\n501\t\n502\t3.2.3 Quantities to be reported\n503\t• For specific sound events or short measurement intervals: Levels should be logged using\n504\tA weighting and a fast time integration. A suitable metric for reporting a frequency-weighted and\n505\ttime-integrated level is the maximum sound pressure level LAF,max . During the same measurement\n506\tperiod, the continuous equivalent “average” level\n507\tLAeq,T should be reported, including the duration\n508\tT of the observation.\n509\t• Match statistics (1): Data logging of continuous\n510\tequivalent levels in periods of 1 s, 1 min and for\n511\tother relevant event durations, e.g., LAeq values\n512\tfor each match quarter or half is recommended.\n513\tFor these longer term measurements it is desirable to report the percent exceedance (statistical)\n514\tlevels LAFNT , the acoustic percentiles, as defined\n515\tin [17]. Recommended, N = 1, 5, or 10 as metrics\n516\tof longer term maximum levels during the match,\n517\tand N = 90, or 95 as an estimate of the minimum\n518\tlevels, which could serve as estimates of the background noise.\n519\t\n520\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n521\t\n522\t• Field validation of the system levels (optional):\n523\tParallel measurements of the system for a cross\n524\tcheck of levels with respect to a reference sound\n525\tlevel meter: At a specific reference measurement\n526\tposition, simultaneous Class-1 sound level meter\n527\treading of LAF,max and LAeq,T during outbursts.\n528\t3.4 What makes a good metric?\n529\tBased on the previous considerations, a good crowd\n530\tnoise metric should:\n531\t• Be representative of the actual crowd noise levels\n532\tat different stadium locations, including audience\n533\tareas and/or players’ locations on the pitch. The\n534\tmeasurements should be conducted in the far field.\n535\t• Be robust to non-crowd noise. Transient sounds\n536\tshould not have a prominent effect on the metric.\n537\tIn addition, sounds that are not generated by the\n538\taudience should be excluded from the analysis, as\n539\tit is the case for sounds coming from the stadium\n540\tpublic address system.\n541\t\n542\tPage 7\n543\t\n544\t\f• Be non-intrusive to measure ideally using distributed devices deployed as a fixed system. The\n545\tdevices should be installed either on the roof,\n546\twalls, or any other surface such that the safety in\n547\tthe stadium is never put at risk.\n548\t3.5 Definition of a representative stadium\n549\tcrowd level\n550\tBased on the limitations of current practices and on\n551\tthe requirements outlined above, we define a representative stadium crowd level as a spatially representative estimate of the A-weighted sound pressure level generated by the audience during a live\n552\tsport event, assessed under conditions that are relevant to the experience on the field of play, the pitch.\n553\tThis definition intentionally places the fan-generated\n554\tcontribution and the acoustic exposure of the active players at the centre of the assessment. In this\n555\tcontext, sounds from public address systems, music playback, pyrotechnics, mechanical systems, or\n556\tother non-crowd sources should be excluded from\n557\tthe crowd-level estimate, or explicitly reported as\n558\tseparate contributions when exclusion is not technically possible.\n559\tThe stadium architecture and environmental conditions are part of the acoustic transmission path\n560\tbetween the audience and the receiver positions.\n561\tThey may therefore influence the measured level and\n562\tshould be documented as part of the measurement\n563\tcontext. For cross-venue comparison, it may be useful to distinguish between two complementary quantities: (1) a fan-generated crowd level, aimed at characterising the contribution of the supporters as the\n564\tprimary sound source, and (2) a venue-experienced\n565\tcrowd level, aimed at characterising the combined\n566\tresult of supporter behaviour, stadium geometry, enclosure, and atmospheric conditions at relevant receiver positions. In the present proposal, the priority is to define a transparent and reproducible reference quantity that enables fairer comparisons across\n567\tvenues than single-point peak measurements close to\n568\tthe crowd.\n569\t\n570\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n571\t\n572\t4. Proposed measurement framework\n573\tThe definition of a representative stadium crowd\n574\tlevel requires spatial representativeness. For that reason, the preferred implementation of the proposed\n575\tframework is based on multiple measurement units\n576\tdistributed across the venue and, where relevant, directed towards the field of play. In situations where\n577\tsuch a distributed system is not available, a singleanchor measurement can provide a minimum reporting baseline, provided that all requirements listed in\n578\tSection 3.2 are met and that the limitations of singleposition measurements are explicitly reported.\n579\t4.1 Single-anchor minimum baseline\n580\tA single-anchor metric should be interpreted as\n581\ta minimum baseline rather than as the preferred\n582\tmethod for representative stadium comparison, because the result remains dependent on the selected\n583\tmeasurement position. To ensure spatial representativeness, the single-anchor metric is extended to a\n584\tmulti-anchor estimation in Section 4.2.\n585\t4.1.1 Definition\n586\tThe measurement unit is used to compute a stadium\n587\tcrowd level (SCLmax ). The SCLmax value is obtained\n588\tas the LAF,max value measured over a specific observation period that can be as long as the duration of\n589\tthe sport event or match. The observation period can\n590\talso be related to halves or quarters of a match depending on the sport. If a shorter period is used, e.g.,\n591\tif a specific sound event is targeted, the length of the\n592\t“outburst window” should be explicit and ideally motivated. If i LAF,max values have been logged, then the\n593\tfinal metric SCLmax can be obtained as:\n594\tSCLmax = max {SCLmax,i }\n595\t\n596\t(2)\n597\t\n598\t4.1.2 Why does this metric improve the current\n599\tpractice?\n600\tThe proposed procedure fixes time and frequency\n601\tweightings to be applied to the sound pressure level\n602\treadings, in alignment with current environmental\n603\t\n604\tPage 8\n605\t\n606\t\fand room acoustics guidelines. The procedure reduces the risk of (1) inflating the level reading in case\n607\tof the accidental measurement of a spurious sound\n608\tsource, and (2) reporting sound levels that could have\n609\tbeen measured violating the far field assumption. A\n610\tstrength of the proposed method is that it remains\n611\tsimple enough for its application using either sound\n612\tlevel meters or distributed microphone arrays. The\n613\tmethod is reproducible and transparent.\n614\t\n615\tthe mSCL metric accounts for the variability of levels between audience areas. We will return to this\n616\tpoint in Section 5.2.1.\n617\t4.2.2 Schematic multi-unit stadiums\n618\tA schematic of two systems that can be installed in a\n619\tstereotypical stadium is illustrated in Figure 4 with 8\n620\tand 16 devices. Assuming that the devices are hanging from the ceiling or dedicated trusses, grey circles\n621\tindicate idealised acoustic fields of view, i.e., the area\n622\t\n623\t4.2 Spatially-distributed estimator\n624\tFor cross-venue comparison, the spatially distributed\n625\testimator is the preferred route because it reduces the\n626\tdependence on a priori assumptions about the loudest audience section and provides a more representative description of the crowd contribution across the\n627\tvenue, in line with the definition from Section 3.5.\n628\t(a) Multi-unit system with K=8 devices.\n629\t\n630\t4.2.1 Definition\n631\tThe use of one anchor assumes that one specific device is representative of the stadium under study. The\n632\tchoice of an optimal anchor is therefore biased by\n633\tprior knowledge of the loudest section in the stadium.\n634\tTo objectivise the choice of an “optimal anchor,” it is\n635\tdesirable to employ multiple measurement units distributed in the stadium. In such a setting, the sound\n636\tevents in the stadium are evaluated using multiple\n637\tlooks in a similar sense as adopted in signal detection\n638\ttheory [39], having as many looks —or independent\n639\tobservation points— as units that are used. Hence,\n640\tincreasing the number of devices increases the probability of finding an overall maximum level of the\n641\tstadium. Following the logic of the SCLmax metric,\n642\tthe overall resulting metric can be obtained from the\n643\tmaximum of all maxima. To make a distinction in the\n644\tnotation, we introduce the prefix “m” to the name of\n645\tthe metric. If the SCLmax value of device k is named\n646\tSCLmax,k , then, the mSCLmax metric is obtained as:\n647\tmSCLmax = max {SCLmax,k }\n648\t\n649\t(3)\n650\t\n651\tNote that the mSCL estimation could use more\n652\telaborate ways of combining series of LAF values\n653\tthan the simple formulation in equation (3), so that\n654\t\n655\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n656\t\n657\t(b) Multi-unit system with a higher density of devices\n658\t(K=16).\n659\t\n660\t(c) Three-unit system distributed over the pitch area.\n661\tThis system can be combined with the system in panels (a) or (b), leading to a 9- or 19-device system, respectively.\n662\t\n663\tFigure 4: Schematic of three multi-unit systems for a stereotypical stadium with seating sections around the pitch. The microphone symbols indicate distributed measurement devices. Two\n664\trelevant target areas that could be related to singing and visitors’\n665\tsections are highlighted in blue and red, respectively. Panels (a)\n666\tand (b) represent two systems that are increasingly more accurate than the one-device systems from Figure 1. Although these\n667\tsystems in panels (a) and (b) are still focused on the audience\n668\tarea only, they can be extended to cover the pitch if combined\n669\twith the system from panel (c).\n670\t\n671\tPage 9\n672\t\n673\t\fthat is assumed to be reliably covered by the corresponding device. The seating sections are coloured\n674\tblue for the singing section, red for the visitors section, and grey for the remaining sections. The microphone symbols indicate the measurement device\n675\tlocations.\n676\tTwo simple one-device systems were introduced\n677\tin Figure 1. Figure 1(a) reflects the current GWR\n678\tpractice, targeted at one specific audience area.\n679\tThe system in Figure 4(a) represents a system\n680\twhere arbitrarily two devices on each side of the stadium are placed, with a total of K=8 devices. Under\n681\tthis criterion, the schematic singing section is covered by two devices while the visitors section is still\n682\tnot directly covered by any of the other 6 devices.\n683\tWith the hypothesis that supporters from either the\n684\tsinging or visitors’ sections can lead to the highest\n685\tcrowd noise levels, this system will still provide more\n686\tadvantage to the singing section. The visitors’ cheering will however be much better covered, due to two\n687\tdevices that are close (but not close enough) to the\n688\tvisitors’ area (in red).\n689\tThe system in Figure 4(b) represents a system\n690\twith a fairer coverage of the whole stadium, where\n691\tfour devices are used along each side, with a total\n692\tof K=16 devices. In this case, the visitors will be\n693\tmore accurately followed, giving them the possibility to drive the SCL estimate to them. Even if the visitors do not produce high levels, a comparison of the\n694\tvisitors’ SCL and the SCL estimate for the singing\n695\tsection can lead to an interesting estimate of the stadium atmosphere, particularly for actions led by the\n696\thome or the away team.\n697\tIn order to extend the monitoring of crowd noises\n698\tto other stadium locations, the systems in Figure 4\n699\tcan be combined with one or more devices that cover\n700\tthe pitch area, as schematically drawn in Figure 1(b)\n701\tand Figure 4(c), respectively.\n702\t4.3 Device installation\n703\tOne of the challenges of a projection onto the pitch\n704\tis related to the proper installation of devices that\n705\tare sufficiently close to the pitch. If the stadium is\n706\t\n707\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n708\t\n709\topen there might not be any mounting point above\n710\tthe pitch or the mounting possibilities may be very\n711\tlimited. This is in contrast to indoor stadiums where\n712\tdevices could be mounted on the roof or from trusses.\n713\tAlternatives to ceiling installations [Figure 1(a)], are\n714\tthe installation of microphones alongside the pitch\n715\t[Figure 1(b)] or even the use of microphones as\n716\twearable devices, similar in concept to referee-view\n717\tbroadcast systems in elite football [40]. Under such\n718\tinstallation constraints, accurate projections of a stadium level will require a more elaborate processing\n719\talgorithm but, as pointed out earlier in this study, it\n720\tcould be relevant to study and keep track of historic\n721\tlevels projected to the field such that noise dosimetry\n722\testimates for players can be derived.\n723\t5. Discussion and perspectives for the future\n724\tIn the current study, we proposed a metric for the\n725\tcomparison of stadiums such that the levels of the\n726\tcrowd or “loudness” could be assessed. We presented a high-level description indicating relevant\n727\tconsiderations related to the definition of the measurement locations and the acoustic metrics to be reported, such that future reports of crowd levels are\n728\tbased on valid acoustic measurements in contrast to\n729\tthe current records listed in Table 1.\n730\t5.1 Main recommendations\n731\tThe high-level description of the proposed measurement framework was focused on identifying weak\n732\tchoices, often omitted, in the measurement protocols\n733\tthat have been adopted in previous assessments of\n734\tcrowd noise levels.\n735\tFor a fair cross-venue comparison, spatially distributed measurements should be regarded as the recommended approach to estimate crowd noise levels.\n736\tA single-anchor measurement may be useful as a\n737\ttransparent minimum baseline, but it should not be\n738\tinterpreted as equivalent to a spatially representative\n739\tstadium assessment.\n740\tMore generally, we defined (1) the minimum\n741\tdistance that is required to ensure a far field mea-\n742\t\n743\tPage 10\n744\t\n745\t\fsurement, (2) the recommendation of using fastintegrated A-weighted sound pressure levels, and\n746\t(3) the use of traceable instruments to collect the\n747\tdata.\n748\t5.2 Limitations and future work\n749\t5.2.1 Other statistics instead of the maximum levels\n750\tThe current SCL proposal is focused on estimations\n751\tusing maximum levels. While this choice aligns with\n752\tthe GWR procedure and improves it, it may still provide insufficient information for the appropriate characterisation of crowd noise at a stadium. As part of a\n753\trevised version of the current SCL proposal, the following aspects need to be addressed and refined:\n754\t• Which specific level statistic is best suited to assess\n755\teach individual anchor metric: next to the LAF,max\n756\tlevels, LAeq values or other estimates may be more\n757\tinformative. These extra options may be sport dependent or even sound-event dependent (see Section 3.2.3).\n758\t• The combination of levels from multiple anchors\n759\tusing maximum levels [Equation (3)] may not be\n760\tsufficiently informative of, e.g., an overall maximum level as experienced by a player, or of the\n761\tlevel contrasts between audience sections.\n762\tThe test cases under which the current multi-unit\n763\testimation will be representative and when a more\n764\telaborate combination of crowd levels between units\n765\twill be required needs to be investigated.\n766\t5.2.2 New test cases and crowd noise database\n767\tDue to the high-level nature of the proposed method,\n768\tno test cases are shared in this study. However, it\n769\tis of crucial importance to have established an objective way of characterising crowd noise in stadiums first. The main motivation for this approach is\n770\tthe complex nature and diversity of sound events that\n771\ttake place during a sport event and the great variability that can be observed at different locations in the\n772\tstadium. For an appropriate estimation of stadium\n773\t\n774\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n775\t\n776\tcrowd noise, we also postulate that the players’ experience should be well captured, requiring to focus\n777\ton crowd noise as projected onto the pitch. In addition, considering that many modern stadiums are\n778\tmultiuse and can even have retractable roofs [1], it\n779\tmay be worth to treat multiuse stadiums as separate\n780\tvenues for different sports.\n781\tTo further advance the discussion of these aspects, we need to collect data and develop a database\n782\tof sports venues with reliable estimates of crowd\n783\tnoise.\n784\t5.2.3 Account for the exact acoustic environment\n785\tWe recommend to characterise a stadium based on\n786\tfar-field measurements. For this recommendation we\n787\tlinked the minimum distance for a reliable acoustic\n788\tmeasurement to the lowest frequency of interest. Depending on the fulfilment of that criterion in addition\n789\tto the use of multiple anchor devices, the measurement points and the audience can be very far apart.\n790\tIn this case, a distance compensation algorithm may\n791\tbe required. If this approach is needed, a physical\n792\tcorrection that depends on distance [41, 42], temperature, relative humidity, or any other atmospheric or\n793\tgeometrical factor may be required. These aspects\n794\twill be related to the type of acoustic field of the stadium ranging from open, semi-open, or close, and its\n795\tspecific dimensions. A procedure to obtain a reliable\n796\tsource-dependent transfer function may be needed in\n797\tthe future.\n798\t5.2.4 Possibility of real-time noise mapping\n799\tAlthough we encouraged the use of multiple devices,\n800\twe did not emphasise the wide range of possibilities\n801\toffered by the use of distributed microphone arrays,\n802\tor acoustic cameras. In such a case, using the beamforming technique, local SCLmax values can be projected to a group of seats, obtaining a noise map with\n803\ta detailed grid. This is similar to the classical noise\n804\tmaps in acoustics [43] but more granular because\n805\teach projected point will have its own level trace as\n806\ta function of time. To convert such a map to a static\n807\tmap, any acoustic metric could be applied, e.g., by\n808\t\n809\tPage 11\n810\t\n811\t\fkeeping the maximum obtained from each device, by\n812\taveraging the LAF values, or by using other metrics\n813\tsuch as percentiles applied to the time-varying estimates. These possibilities will be explored in future publications. Note that such noise maps can\n814\tbe employed to complement SCLmax assessments in\n815\tmany different ways, that include building a database\n816\tof historic levels for one stadium or across stadiums\n817\tor for investigating the crowd behaviour for specific\n818\tmatch events (e.g., goals, free throws, or free kicks).\n819\t5.3 Final remarks\n820\tIn this study, we proposed a measurement framework for transparent and reproducible evaluation of\n821\tcrowd noise during sport events. The framework\n822\tdefines a representative stadium crowd level (SCL)\n823\tas a spatially representative estimate of audiencegenerated A-weighted sound pressure levels, with\n824\tspatially distributed measurement as the preferred\n825\troute for cross-venue comparison. A single-anchor\n826\t(SCLmax ) metric is retained as a transparent minimum reporting baseline when distributed measurement is not feasible, but should not be interpreted\n827\t\n828\tas equivalent to a spatially representative stadium assessment. The method is focused on how to use an\n829\tacoustic measurement device that should minimally\n830\thave one microphone, as is the case of the standard\n831\tsound level meters, but it can actually use other devices.\n832\tThe main purpose of the current study is to raise\n833\tawareness of the potential technical flaws of previous crowd noise measurements, to overcome these\n834\tissues in future reports targeted to either scientific or\n835\tgeneral audiences. We also suggest that a fair crowd\n836\tnoise estimate should not only be representative of\n837\tthe levels in supporters’ areas but should also account\n838\tfor the players’ experience on the pitch. We invite the\n839\tscientific community to discuss, scrutinise, and further develop measurement guidelines, so that future\n840\tstadium level reports meet all the minimum acoustic\n841\tstandards. Such a synergy could also help to establish a procedure valid not only for mobile systems\n842\t(point-based measurements) but also valid for installations of fixed systems to which an uncertainty can\n843\tbe attributed. Such guidelines can help the future fair\n844\tcomparison of crowd noise levels across stadiums.\n845\t\n846\t6. References\n847\t[1] G. Siebein, K. Siebein, J. Wrightson, J. Solway, and R. Patel, “Large-venue acoustics: Arenas, stadiums, and amphitheaters,”\n848\tAcoustics Today, vol. 20, pp. 55–65, 2024. https://doi.org/10.1121/AT.2024.20.1.55.\n849\t[2] J. Oldfield, R. Oldfield, and D. Holmes, “The effects of different types of crowd noise on penalty taking performance in football,”\n850\tInt. J. Sport Exerc. Psychol., vol. 24, pp. 67–84, 2026. https://doi.org/10.1080/1612197X.2024.2432996.\n851\t[3] J. Taylor, S. Mellalieu, N. James, and D. Shearer, “The influence of match location, quality of opposition, and match status on\n852\ttechnical performance in professional association football,” Journal of Sports Sciences, vol. 26, pp. 885–895, 2008. https:\n853\t//doi.org/10.1080/02640410701836887.\n854\t[4] A. Barnard, S. Porter, J. Bostron, R. terMeulen, and S. Hambric, “Evaluation of crowd noise levels during college football games,”\n855\tNoise Control Eng. J., vol. 59, pp. 667–680, 2011. https://doi.org/10.3397/1.3654144.\n856\t[5] C. Unkelbach and D. Memmert, “Crowd noise as a cue in referee decisions contributes to the home advantage,” J. Sport Exerc.\n857\tPsychol., vol. 32, pp. 483–498, 2010. https://doi.org/10.1123/jsep.32.4.483.\n858\t[6] Guinness World Records, “Loudest crowd roar at a sports stadium,” 2014. www.guinnessworldrecords.com/worldrecords/loudest-crowd-roar-at-a-sports-stadium (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n859\t[7] Guinness World Records, “Seattle Seahawks fans cause minor earthquake with world record crowd roar,” 2013.\n860\twww.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/12/seattle-seahawks-fans-cause-minor-earthquakewith-world-record-crowd-roar-53285 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n861\t[8] Chiefs, “Records were broken today at Arrowhead Stadium!,” 2013. www.chiefs.com/news/records-broken11499403 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n862\t\n863\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n864\t\n865\tPage 12\n866\t\n867\t\f[9] Saturday Down South, “Tennessee breaks decibel record as Neyland stadium roars against Georgia,” 2023.\n868\twww.saturdaydownsouth.com/news/college-football/tennessee-breaks-decibel-record-asneyland-stadium-roars-against-georgia/ (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n869\t[10] Guinness World Records,\n870\t“Seattle Seahawks break record for loudest stadium crowd roar,”\n871\t2013.\n872\twww.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/9/seattle-seahawks-break-record-for-loudeststadium-crowd-roar-51331 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n873\t[11] The Seattle Times, “How UW won perhaps the loudest college football game ever played 30 years ago against\n874\tNebraska,” 2022. www.seattletimes.com/sports/washington-huskies-football/how-uw-won-perhapsthe-loudest-college-football-game-ever-played (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n875\t[12] Everton FC, “Top 5 loudest recorded crowd noises in football stadiums,” 2025. Facebook post, www.facebook.com/\n876\tEvertonOnceABlueAlwaysABlue/posts/top-5-loudest-recorded-crowd-noises-ever-infootball-stadiums1-besiktass-vodafon/1367726645354829/ (Accessed: 23 June 2026).\n877\t[13] Guinness World Records, “Galatasaray—Loudest crowd roar at a sport stadium:\n878\twww.youtube.com/watch?v=H96QXhrE1Bw (Accessed: 16 July 2026).\n879\t\n880\t131.76 dB,” 2011. https://\n881\t\n882\t[14] Guinness World Records, “Loudest crowd roar at an indoor sports event,” 2017. www.guinnessworldrecords.com/worldrecords/loudest-crowd-roar-at-a-sports-stadium-(indoors) (Accessed 23 June 2026).\n883\t[15] Knoxville News Sentinel, “How loud was Neyland stadium when Tennessee football beat Alabama? was it dangerous?,” 2022.\n884\thttps://eu.knoxnews.com/story/sports/college/university-of-tennessee/football/2022/10/\n885\t19/tennessee-football-fans-neyland-stadium-noise-decibels-alabama/69573565007/ (Accessed:\n886\t1 June 2026).\n887\t[16] Acentech, “Making some noise: We’re questioning those world record stadium sound levels.” www.acentech.com/\n888\tresources/making-some-noise-were-questioning-those-world-record-stadium-sound-levels/,\n889\t2019. (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n890\t[17] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 1996-1:2016 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of\n891\tenvironmental noise – Part 1: Basic quantities and assessment procedures,” 2016. https://www.iso.org/standard/\n892\t59765.html.\n893\t[18] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 1996-2:2017 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of environmental noise – Part 2: Determination of sound pressure levels,” 2017. https://www.iso.org/standard/59766.html.\n894\t[19] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO/PAS 1996-3:2022 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of\n895\tenvironmental noise – Part 3: Objective method for the measurement of prominence of impulsive sounds and for adjustment of\n896\tLAeq,” 2022. https://www.iso.org/standard/77035.html.\n897\t[20] A. Barnard, “A proposed technique for measuring and comparing crowd noise from sporting events,” in Inter-Noise\n898\t2015, pp. 366–373, 2015. https://ince.publisher.ingentaconnect.com/content/ince/incecp/2015/\n899\t00000250/00000007/art00037.\n900\t[21] W. Van Ransbeeck, N. De Poortere, M. Kok, and S. Verhulst, “Characteristics of personal sound and noise exposure at large-scale\n901\tmusic events,” J. Audio Eng. Soc., vol. 72, pp. 901–912, 2024. https://doi.org/10.17743/jaes.2022.0184.\n902\t[22] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 9612:2025 Acoustics — Determination of occupational noise exposure —\n903\tMethodology,” 2025.\n904\t[23] E. Zwicker, G. Flottorp, and S. Stevens, “Critical band width in loudness summation,” J. Acoust. Soc. Am., vol. 29, pp. 548–557,\n905\t1957. https://doi.org/10.1121/1.1908963.\n906\t[24] A. Osses, G. Felix Greco, and R. Merino-Martı́nez, “Considerations for the perceptual evaluation of steady-state and timevarying sounds using psychoacoustic metrics,” in Forum Acusticum, (Torino, Italy), pp. 6319–6326, 2023. https://doi.org/\n907\t10.61782/fa.2023.0600.\n908\t[25] B. Moore, An Introduction to the Psychology of Hearing. Leiden, The Netherlands: Brill, 6 ed., 2013.\n909\t[26] D. Houser, W. Yost, R. Burkard, J. Finneran, C. Reichmuth, and J. Mulsow, “A review of the history, development and application\n910\tof auditory weighting functions in humans and marine mammals,” J. Acoust. Soc. Am., vol. 141, pp. 1371–1413, 2017. https:\n911\t//doi.org/10.1121/1.4976086.\n912\t\n913\tAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n914\t\n915\tPage 13\n916\t\n917\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "847813e3-e201-4568-8357-b00ca57f08d4", "uuid": "626c9c7d-687b-4733-b78e-9d7ee182963b", "timestamp": "2026-07-22T07:24:12.804Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.18922.txt", "content": "Towards a reproducible cross-venue method for\nquantifying crowd noise in stadiums\nAlejandro Osses, Bente Ackermans, Helmer Nuijens, Rick Scholte\nSorama BV, Eindhoven, the Netherlands\n\narXiv:2607.18922v1 [eess.AS] 21 Jul 2026\n\nalejandro.osses@sorama.eu,\n\nAbstract\nPublic claims about the “loudest stadium” have been\nbased on an instantaneous peak dB(A) reading measured at a single point, as popularised by the Guinness\nWorld Records “loudest crowd roar” category. The current record dates from 2014, where a maximum level of\n142.2 dB(A) was registered. While compelling, those\nmeasurements lack standardisation, omitting relevant information such as the specific instrument that was used,\nthe usage of time weighting, and the number of measurement positions that were tested. This lack of information does not allow a well-founded scientific comparison across sport venues. This study proposes a measurement framework in which spatially distributed acoustic\nmeasurement is the recommended route for a representative cross-venue comparison, while a single-anchor measurement can only serve as a minimum reporting baseline\nwhen distributed measurements are not feasible.\n\n1. Introduction\nSport venues with passionate supporters are\nrenowned for their lively and engaging atmosphere,\nin which sound plays a central role. The acoustic\nenvironment in a stadium is not just a by-product of\nspectatorship, but it is rather an active contributor to\nthe dynamics of the game [1]. In particular, players\non the pitch are influenced —both positively and\nnegatively— by the presence of crowd noise [2].\nElevated sound levels can enhance motivation and\nperceived home advantage, while at the same time\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\ninfo@sorama.eu\n\ninterfere with communication, concentration, and\ndecision making [3–5]. As such, the notion of a\n“loud stadium” is inherently tied to how sound is\nperceived by players during a game.\nBeyond its impact on players, sound in stadiums has additional roles. It contributes to the overall\nspectator experience, reinforces collective engagement among supporters, and influences how events\nare perceived through broadcast media. These multiple roles make sound a key parameter in the evaluation of stadium atmosphere. Despite this, the quantification of “crowd noise” is typically focused on\nsimplified metrics, often detached from the actual experience on the pitch.\nMany crowd noise records exist and are often reported in press articles or compiled by organisations\nsuch as Guinness World Records (GWR), as summarised in Table 1.\nThe current loudest venue was registered in 2014\nat Arrowhead stadium during an American football\nmatch [6]. The record was obtained as a peak reading from a sound level meter providing a level of\n142.2 dB(A). It is unclear which specific instrument\nwas used, where it was located, and how this reading compares to the history of levels across different\nmeasurement positions, matches, and seasons. These\nobservations are also valid for the other venues that\nare listed in Table 1.\nWhile peak values are straightforward to com-\n\nPage 1\n\n\fTable 1: List of loudest stadiums with a reported acoustic level. Most of these levels have been reported in A-weighted dB values,\ndB(A), however, when not explicitly mentioned, the unit is marked as “dB.”\nDate\nSep 29, 2014\nDec 2, 2013\nOct 13, 2013\nNov 8, 2023\nSep 15, 2013\nSep 19, 1999\n2007\nMar 18, 2011\nNot reported\nFeb 13, 2017\nNov 5, 2024\nAug 24, 2025\nOct 15, 2022\n\nHome team\nKansas City Chiefs\nSeattle Seahawks\nKansas City Chiefs\nTennessee\nSeattle Seahawks\nUniversity of Washington\nBeşiktaş\nGalatasaray\nFenerbahçe\nKansas Jayhawks\nCeltic\nEverton FC\nTennessee\n\nVenue\nArrowhead stadium\nLumen field\nArrowhead stadium\nNeyland stadium\nLumen field\nHusky stadium\nVodafone Park\nAli Sami Yen stadium\nŞükrü Saracoğlu stadium\nAllen Fieldhouse\nCeltic Park\nHill Dickinson stadium\nNeyland stadium\n\nmunicate, they are limited from a scientific perspective. In particular, such values do not ensure\nrepresentativity or reproducibility across venues and\nevents [16]. This limitation is particularly relevant\nwhen the quantity of interest is the sound as experienced by players, rather than the maximum level at a\nsingle measurement location. Several limitations that\nare associated with current practices are:\n• The use of a peak reading is not aligned with standard acoustic procedures because transient or other\nextraneous sounds are typically not representative\nof the sound sources under investigation [17, 18].\nActually, transient sounds —as those that can be\npicked up by a peak reading— often require a separate treatment [19].\n• If instead of a peak reading, the estimate of maximum levels is based on fast-integrated sound pressure levels, the estimations will be lowered by at\nleast 10 dB [16], a non-negligible difference. This\ndifference is illustrated later in Figure 2.\n• The measurement position seems to be chosen\nbased on intuition rather than using any spatial or\nacoustic criterion. Employing an acoustic criterion\ncould ensure, for example, that the measurements\nare collected in the stable acoustic far field.\n• Because there is no spatial criterion to choose the\nmeasurement locations, there is no guarantee that\nthe highest crowd levels are being registered.\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\nCity\nKansas City, USA\nSeattle, USA\nKansas City, USA\nKnoxville, USA\nSeattle, USA\nSeattle, USA\nIstanbul, Turkey\nIstanbul, Turkey\nIstanbul, Turkey\nLawrence, Kansas, USA\nGlasgow, Scotland\nLiverpool, UK\nKnoxville, USA\n\nSport\nAmerican football\nAmerican football\nAmerican football\nAmerican football\nAmerican football\nAmerican football\nFootball\nFootball\nFootball\nBasketball\nFootball\nFootball\nAmerican football\n\nLevel\n142.2 dB(A)\n137.6 dB(A)\n137.5 dB\n137.0 dB\n136.6 dB\n133.6 dB\n132.0 dB\n131.76 dB(A)\n131.0 dB\n130.4 dB(A)\n129.0 dB\n126.0 dB\n125.4 dB\n\nSource\n[6]\n[7]\n[8]\n[9]\n[10]\n[11]\n[12]\n[13]\n[12]\n[14]\n[12]\n[12]\n[15]\n\nIn other words, the current practices can lead to\nnon-representative results or even to invalid acoustic\nmeasurements. The goal of this study is to establish the foundations of a more rigorous measurement\nprotocol, so that the reliability of future crowd-noise\nestimates is increased. The adoption of such a protocol will also allow to (1) characterise the crowd\nbehaviour during specific match actions, making a\ndistinction of the supporters’ behaviour during, e.g.,\na goal or a free throw [4]; (2) assess noise exposure\nmetrics [20,21] as typically evaluated in hearing conservation programs of noise at work [22]; (3) project\nthe estimates to predict exterior sound pressure levels, outside the stadium (e.g., [4]).\nIn this study we introduce a method to assess\ncrowd levels at stadiums using one or multiple acoustic measurement devices. The method can use single microphone devices, such as sound level meters,\nbut can also use distributed microphone arrays, also\nknown as acoustic cameras. The structure of this paper is as follows: We start by identifying the limitations of the current crowd noise estimate (Section 2) and defining the criteria that must be fulfilled to ensure its reliable and representative quantification (Section 3). Based on those requirements,\nwe first define a representative stadium crowd level\nand then describe a measurement framework (Section 4) in which spatially distributed measurements\nare the preferred implementation for a cross-venue\ncomparison. We focus on practical and technical as-\n\nPage 2\n\n\fpects that can lead to an objective and scalable noise\nmonitoring system in indoor, semi-open, and outdoor sport venues. Finally we emphasise the scope\nof the method and indicate the limitations of the current proposal with an eye on future extensions of the\nmethod.\n\n(a) Current device positioning as used in the GWR procedure.\n\n2. Loudest crowd roar: Current practice\nDespite the omission of specific technical details in\nthe GWR procedure, in the category “loudest crowd\nroar at a sports stadium,” the method has been systematically used in the last decades [6–11, 14]. The\n“loudest crowd roar” or, better said, the highest\ncrowd noise level 1 was claimed to be a peak dB(A)\nreading during a specific match moment. From press\nresources (see, e.g., pictures from [6,10]) can be seen\nthat the metric has been based on point measurements collected with a Class 1 sound level meter Larson Davis 831, which was located very close to the\ncrowd. A schematic stadium illustrating the positioning of such a single measurement device is depicted\nin Figure 1(a).\nThe GWR approach disregards the impact of the\ncrowd on the pitch and it does not give the possibility to supporters in other audience areas to become\nthe loudest fans. These drawbacks can be partly mitigated if the measurement device is targeted to the\npitch, as depicted in Figure 1(b). We will come back\nto this discussion later, when multiple-device systems are introduced.\n2.1 Why is a peak dB(A) reading ambiguous?\nPeak levels are not typically used in environmental\nnor architectural acoustic standards. The main reason is that acoustic metrics have been developed to\naccount for relevant aspects of human sound perception. One of these aspects is the difficulty of our ears\n1\n\nDespite the fact that the term loudness or loudest crowd has\nbeen widely used, we will refrain as much as possible from its\nuse. The reason is that loudness is actually the perceptual counterpart of sound pressure levels, expressed in Sones and not in\ndB as it is the case for sound levels [23, 24]. We will instead\nrefer to “crowd noise estimates” or “crowd levels.”\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n(b) One-device system that is pointed to the middle of the pitch.\nThis arbitrary point will capture sounds coming from multiple\naudience sections.\n\nFigure 1: Generic stadium showing the pitch (in green) and audience areas (in grey), using one measurement device (microphone symbol). Panel (a) reflects the device positioning as it\nhas been so far used for crowd noise measurements, targeting a\nspecific audience area, which is assumed to produce the highest\ncrowd-noise levels. Two drawbacks of the current approach are:\n(1) supporters in other sections do not get the possibility to become the loudest fans, because there is no measurement device\nin their neighbourhood, and (2) the impact of the crowd onto\nthe pitch, where the players are performing, is unknown. The\none-device set-up shown in Panel (b) partly copes with those\nlimitations as it is pointed to the pitch which, by design, receives\nthe level contribution from all the audience areas.\n\nto react to transient sounds. The ear is a “sluggish”\norgan that requires a time of about 200 ms to react\nto sudden level changes (see [25], p. 64), resulting in\nsounds that are perceived as a slower and smoother\ntime-varying envelope, despite the strongly-varying\ntime information contained in a sound waveform.\nHistorically, time weightings were adopted for tracking changes in level by a sound level meter due to\nearly physical limitations of the old analog volume\nunit (VU) meters. Many years after, the fast integration time constant of 125 ms is well accepted as\na correlate to the slower-varying perceived envelope\nand it is widely recommended in multiple international standards. According to ISO 1996-1 [17] that\ndefines basic quantities used in environmental acoustics, two suitable metrics to characterise sound events\n\nPage 3\n\n\fare the fast-integrated maximum level LAF,max and\ncontinuous equivalent level LAeq . The subindex “A”\nindicates the use of the A-weighting curve, whose\nuse is another add-on to the level assessments that\nhas been inspired by perceptual aspects, reflecting\nthe ear’s frequency-dependent sensitivity [26].\nConsidering all these arguments, a peak reading\ndoes not consider the time required to integrate a\nsound, and therefore is not a suitable measure of perceived amplitudes. In fact, the exclusion of transient\nsounds is a common acoustic practice (e.g., [18]).\nMore generally, a peak reading can be seen as an\nestimator of a maximum value in a waveform. The\nwaveform of a goal moment is shown in light blue\n\nin Figure 2(a) and its peak maximum is indicated\nby a blue square marker. The adoption of a fast\ntime weighting will naturally smooth the waveform,\nconverting it into a much slower time varying envelope (thick pink trace). The fast-integrated maximum in panel (a) (pink circle marker) is 3.8 times\nsmaller than the peak maximum reading. The maximum estimates and the envelope are expressed in\ndB in panel (b), emphasising that for this example\nthe peak reading overestimates the maximum level\nby 11.6 dB.\nAnother important aspect is that the measuring\ndevice will only be able to capture sounds that are under its microphone acoustic overload point. Acoustic overload points represent the maximum physical\nlevel of a measuring device before saturating, and\nare reported in dB(Z), i.e., before any time or frequency weighting is applied. Typical overload points\nare between 130 and 150 dB(Z). The reported overload point for the Larson Davis 831 sound level meter is 143 dB(Z) [27], which is suspiciously close to\nthe reported 142.2 dB(A). This could mean that the\nGWR measurement might have been pushed down\nby the saturation point of the measurement device.\n2.2 Focus on the audience, the players, or both?\n\nFigure 2: Goal moment for a football match between PSV Eindhoven and RKC Waalwijk on 19 May 2024 from the Dutch Eredivisie. Ten seconds around the exact goal moment are drawn.\nPanel (a) shows a waveform (in light blue) measured by an\nNTi XL2 Class 1 sound level meter which has a maximum of\n24.4 Pascals or 121.7 dB (blue square marker). The pink trace\nshows the temporal envelope after the waveform was subjected\nto a fast time integration. The maximum of that curve is 6.4 Pascals or 110.1 dB (pink circle marker). Panel (b) shows the envelope and the maximum estimates expressed in dB. The difference\nbetween the maximum level estimated from the peak reading and\nfrom the fast-integrated levels is 11.6 dB (reduction by a factor\nof 3.8).\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\nSo far, crowd noise estimates have been focused on\nsounds produced by the audience. This is probably\nthe most straightforward way to estimate the supporters’ strength and commitment to the team they support. We must not forget, however, that the supporters are primarily driven by the active players on the\npitch and their actions (e.g., [4]). If players can have\nsuch a direct impact on the supporters, why are the\ncrowd noise estimates not focused on sound levels as\nprojected onto the players?\nA well-known case of the negative impact of\ncrowd noise on a player was reported in 2017 during\na football match between Beşiktaş and RB Leipzig\nat the Vodafone stadium (ranked 7th in Table 1) valid\nfor the UEFA Champions League [28]. During the\ngame, the German player Timo Werner (RB Leipzig)\nrequested the use of ear plugs and finally left the\n\nPage 4\n\n\fpitch after suffering from circulation problems as a\nconsequence of the loud perception of the Beşiktaş’\nsupporter roars.\nFocusing on sounds on the pitch seems to be a\nstrategic choice because the reference measurement\npoints will be confined in a smaller area with known\ndimensions, facilitating the comparison across stadiums. A schematic example of a straightforward\npoint to spot on the pitch, the middle point of the\nvenue, is illustrated in Figure 1(b). What needs to\nbe investigated is whether crowd levels on the pitch\nwill indeed be more representative of the overall atmosphere in the stadium compared to an evaluation\npurely focused on the audience. A data-driven discussion of this issue can help identify the most effective approach.\n3. Improving the crowd noise estimation\n3.1 Frequencies of interest and their far field\nEnvironmental and room acoustics measurements\nimplicitly assume that the data are collected satisfying a far field condition. The far field relates to\nthe region in space where the underlying wavefronts\nof the sound source can be approximated as planar\nwaves. The far field recommendation can be linked\nto the wavelength of the lowest frequency of interest.\n3.1.1 Target frequency range\nFor stadiums and particularly focusing on sounds\nemitted by a crowd, we suggest the target frequency\nrange between 100 and 8000 Hz (see, e.g., Chapter 4\nfrom [29]). This choice offers a pragmatic trade-off\nto capture:\n• Fundamental frequency f0 of loud voices (90270 Hz): For male voices the average f0 for vowels\nis 120 Hz, between 80 and 180 Hz, and for female\nvoices is 200 Hz, between 150 and 260 Hz. A rise\nof about 10 Hz is expected for loud voices [30].\n• The effective range of vocal energy\n(300–3000 Hz): This range contains the formant\ncomponents of vowels and voiced consonants [31].\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n• Consonant content (3000–8000 Hz) as found in\nfricative consonants (e.g., “s,” “sh,” and “th”) and,\nto a lesser extent in plosive consonants (e.g., “t,”\n“k,” “b,” “d,” etc.) [31].\n• Whistles and clapping transients as well as sharp\ncheering bursts (3000–8000 Hz) (e.g., [32]).\n• Chant detection (300–3000 Hz): This frequency\nrange allows to keep all the relevant information\nto get intelligible speech (e.g., [33]).\nBy focusing on measurements between 100 and\n8000 Hz, very low frequency components that are\nunlikely related to crowds are excluded. Although\nthis filtering seems very rough, slow frequency fluctuations (<20 Hz) that are relevant for the perception\nof sound reality [34, 35] are not affected. Those slow\nfluctuations are well retained by the temporal envelope in the 100-8000 Hz range [34].\n3.1.2 Measurement distance: Far field criterion\nTo ensure a far-field measurement under the classical acoustic assumptions, the lowest target frequency\n––corresponding to the longest wavelength—- must\nsatisfy the far-field criterion. This wavelength represents the most restrictive condition for the validity of\nthe far-field approximation.\nIn this study, we adopt the simplified relation:\nrcritical = 2 · λ\n\n(1)\n\nwhere rcritical is the minimum distance in meters between the sound source (i.e., the crowd) and the measurement position required to ensure the free-field\nconditions, and λ is the wavelength in meters associated with the lowest frequency of interest. 2\nA far-field measurement ensures that the measurement position lies outside both the reactive\nnear-field and the transition region, where spherical\n2\n\nEquation (1) is independent of the size of the sound source\nunder investigation. Such independence \u0001derives from the Fraunhofer distance where rcritical = 2 · D2 /λ. Equation (1) will\nbe obtained when the characteristic dimension D of the source\nis assumed to be acoustically small, conservatively using D = λ\n(more generally with D ≤ λ).\n\nPage 5\n\n\fdation is not met for the two front-most seat rows,\nwhich are still in near field. For the same schematic\nstadium, Figure 3(b) shows a measurement position\nthat meets with suggested far-field criterion.\n3.2 Requirements for a cross-venue\nstadium-noise metric\n\n(a)\n\nTo ensure the comparability of a crowd-noise metric\nacross stadiums we suggest some criteria related to:\n(1) the measurements to be conducted, and (2) the\ntraceability of the instruments to be used.\n3.2.1 Measurements\n• Level readings (1): The measurements should be\nbased on sound pressure level readings in dB(A).\n\n(b)\n\nFigure 3: Position of a measuring device —shown as a\nschematic microphone— which is either (a) in front of the\nstands, as it could be done if a sound level meter is used for\nthe measurements, or (b) on the roof, as a fixed installation, as it\ncould be done when using a weatherproof continuous monitoring microphone or a microphone array. The critical distance dcrit\nis shown as the boundary between the near and far fields. The\nshaded areas represent the position in space where we discourage to obtain crowd level estimates.\n\nspreading and stable radiation conditions can be assumed [36].\nConsidering that λ = c/f low , with c being the\nspeed of sound equal to ∼340 m/s in air and f low =\n100 Hz being the lowest target frequency, and replacing these values in equation (1) result in a pragmatic minimum distance criterion rcritical of 6.8 m\nwith respect to the audience area. 3 In larger stadium\ngeometries or highly reflective environments, additional validation may be required. Figure 3(a) shows\na schematic situation where the rcritical recommen3\n\nIf for convenience a nominal rcritical of 8 m is used, the minimum frequency of interest f low is extended down to 85 Hz.\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n• Level readings (2): The levels should use a time\nintegration equal to or greater than 125 ms, as defined for a fast time weighting [37]. A slow time\nweighting could also be adopted (time constant of\n1 s), but longer time constants will generally be\nless sensitive to sudden crowd cheers. We suggest\nto adopt the standard fast time integration.\n• Location (1): The measurement points should be\nspatially meaningful: the exact position should be\nbased on an objective criterion. The measurement\npoint should dominantly capture human-generated\nsounds during the “observation period.”\n• Location (2): The distance between each measurement device and the audience area should be reported. The microphone(s) of the device should\nbe 1.5 m or farther from any obstructing surface\nand pointed towards the audience (e.g., see section A.4 in [38]).\n• Data integrity: The crowd noise estimate should\nbe derived from sound levels that only contain actual crowd noise. Sounds from electronic amplification systems should be excluded from the\ncrowd-level estimate where possible, or explicitly\nreported as separate contributions. Non-electronic\nsupporter-generated instruments, such as drums,\n\nPage 6\n\n\fhorns or vuvuzelas, should be reported separately\nor treated according to sport- and league-specific\nreporting rules.\n3.2.2 Traceability of the measurements\n• The measurement device should have a Class 1\nlevel accuracy. We refer to “Class 1 level accuracy” devices to (1) sound level meters that comply with IEC 61672-1 [37], or (2) microphone arrays for which a frequency response measured at\nan angle of 0 degrees (in front of the device), complies with the acceptance limits defined in Table 3\nfrom [37]. These limits should be met for the target\nfrequency range of the analyses.\n• The dynamic range of operation of the instrument\nshould be reported. The target maximum levels\nshould be below the acoustic overload point. If\nthere is a risk of saturation during the measurements, this should be explicitly stated.\n\n• Match statistics (2): Relevant match statistics\nmight be sport related. In that case, comparisons across stadiums can be difficult because\neach stadium constitutes a different source-pathreceiver system, where the source, i.e., the supporters are very different from sport to sport. It\nmay thus be relevant to consider the construction\nof within-sport databases, with the technical argument that the sound-source dependent transfer\nfunction of a stadium varies from sport to sport [1].\nMulti-purpose sport venues may then have different crowd levels when used for different sports.\n3.3 Field calibration and standards alignment\n• Field calibration: The measurement devices\nshould be checked for field calibration before and\nafter the events, so that drift logs are registered.\nNext to the field calibration, meteorological information (temperature and relative humidity) is desirable to be recorded.\n\n3.2.3 Quantities to be reported\n• For specific sound events or short measurement intervals: Levels should be logged using\nA weighting and a fast time integration. A suitable metric for reporting a frequency-weighted and\ntime-integrated level is the maximum sound pressure level LAF,max . During the same measurement\nperiod, the continuous equivalent “average” level\nLAeq,T should be reported, including the duration\nT of the observation.\n• Match statistics (1): Data logging of continuous\nequivalent levels in periods of 1 s, 1 min and for\nother relevant event durations, e.g., LAeq values\nfor each match quarter or half is recommended.\nFor these longer term measurements it is desirable to report the percent exceedance (statistical)\nlevels LAFNT , the acoustic percentiles, as defined\nin [17]. Recommended, N = 1, 5, or 10 as metrics\nof longer term maximum levels during the match,\nand N = 90, or 95 as an estimate of the minimum\nlevels, which could serve as estimates of the background noise.\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n• Field validation of the system levels (optional):\nParallel measurements of the system for a cross\ncheck of levels with respect to a reference sound\nlevel meter: At a specific reference measurement\nposition, simultaneous Class-1 sound level meter\nreading of LAF,max and LAeq,T during outbursts.\n3.4 What makes a good metric?\nBased on the previous considerations, a good crowd\nnoise metric should:\n• Be representative of the actual crowd noise levels\nat different stadium locations, including audience\nareas and/or players’ locations on the pitch. The\nmeasurements should be conducted in the far field.\n• Be robust to non-crowd noise. Transient sounds\nshould not have a prominent effect on the metric.\nIn addition, sounds that are not generated by the\naudience should be excluded from the analysis, as\nit is the case for sounds coming from the stadium\npublic address system.\n\nPage 7\n\n\f• Be non-intrusive to measure ideally using distributed devices deployed as a fixed system. The\ndevices should be installed either on the roof,\nwalls, or any other surface such that the safety in\nthe stadium is never put at risk.\n3.5 Definition of a representative stadium\ncrowd level\nBased on the limitations of current practices and on\nthe requirements outlined above, we define a representative stadium crowd level as a spatially representative estimate of the A-weighted sound pressure level generated by the audience during a live\nsport event, assessed under conditions that are relevant to the experience on the field of play, the pitch.\nThis definition intentionally places the fan-generated\ncontribution and the acoustic exposure of the active players at the centre of the assessment. In this\ncontext, sounds from public address systems, music playback, pyrotechnics, mechanical systems, or\nother non-crowd sources should be excluded from\nthe crowd-level estimate, or explicitly reported as\nseparate contributions when exclusion is not technically possible.\nThe stadium architecture and environmental conditions are part of the acoustic transmission path\nbetween the audience and the receiver positions.\nThey may therefore influence the measured level and\nshould be documented as part of the measurement\ncontext. For cross-venue comparison, it may be useful to distinguish between two complementary quantities: (1) a fan-generated crowd level, aimed at characterising the contribution of the supporters as the\nprimary sound source, and (2) a venue-experienced\ncrowd level, aimed at characterising the combined\nresult of supporter behaviour, stadium geometry, enclosure, and atmospheric conditions at relevant receiver positions. In the present proposal, the priority is to define a transparent and reproducible reference quantity that enables fairer comparisons across\nvenues than single-point peak measurements close to\nthe crowd.\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n4. Proposed measurement framework\nThe definition of a representative stadium crowd\nlevel requires spatial representativeness. For that reason, the preferred implementation of the proposed\nframework is based on multiple measurement units\ndistributed across the venue and, where relevant, directed towards the field of play. In situations where\nsuch a distributed system is not available, a singleanchor measurement can provide a minimum reporting baseline, provided that all requirements listed in\nSection 3.2 are met and that the limitations of singleposition measurements are explicitly reported.\n4.1 Single-anchor minimum baseline\nA single-anchor metric should be interpreted as\na minimum baseline rather than as the preferred\nmethod for representative stadium comparison, because the result remains dependent on the selected\nmeasurement position. To ensure spatial representativeness, the single-anchor metric is extended to a\nmulti-anchor estimation in Section 4.2.\n4.1.1 Definition\nThe measurement unit is used to compute a stadium\ncrowd level (SCLmax ). The SCLmax value is obtained\nas the LAF,max value measured over a specific observation period that can be as long as the duration of\nthe sport event or match. The observation period can\nalso be related to halves or quarters of a match depending on the sport. If a shorter period is used, e.g.,\nif a specific sound event is targeted, the length of the\n“outburst window” should be explicit and ideally motivated. If i LAF,max values have been logged, then the\nfinal metric SCLmax can be obtained as:\nSCLmax = max {SCLmax,i }\n\n(2)\n\n4.1.2 Why does this metric improve the current\npractice?\nThe proposed procedure fixes time and frequency\nweightings to be applied to the sound pressure level\nreadings, in alignment with current environmental\n\nPage 8\n\n\fand room acoustics guidelines. The procedure reduces the risk of (1) inflating the level reading in case\nof the accidental measurement of a spurious sound\nsource, and (2) reporting sound levels that could have\nbeen measured violating the far field assumption. A\nstrength of the proposed method is that it remains\nsimple enough for its application using either sound\nlevel meters or distributed microphone arrays. The\nmethod is reproducible and transparent.\n\nthe mSCL metric accounts for the variability of levels between audience areas. We will return to this\npoint in Section 5.2.1.\n4.2.2 Schematic multi-unit stadiums\nA schematic of two systems that can be installed in a\nstereotypical stadium is illustrated in Figure 4 with 8\nand 16 devices. Assuming that the devices are hanging from the ceiling or dedicated trusses, grey circles\nindicate idealised acoustic fields of view, i.e., the area\n\n4.2 Spatially-distributed estimator\nFor cross-venue comparison, the spatially distributed\nestimator is the preferred route because it reduces the\ndependence on a priori assumptions about the loudest audience section and provides a more representative description of the crowd contribution across the\nvenue, in line with the definition from Section 3.5.\n(a) Multi-unit system with K=8 devices.\n\n4.2.1 Definition\nThe use of one anchor assumes that one specific device is representative of the stadium under study. The\nchoice of an optimal anchor is therefore biased by\nprior knowledge of the loudest section in the stadium.\nTo objectivise the choice of an “optimal anchor,” it is\ndesirable to employ multiple measurement units distributed in the stadium. In such a setting, the sound\nevents in the stadium are evaluated using multiple\nlooks in a similar sense as adopted in signal detection\ntheory [39], having as many looks —or independent\nobservation points— as units that are used. Hence,\nincreasing the number of devices increases the probability of finding an overall maximum level of the\nstadium. Following the logic of the SCLmax metric,\nthe overall resulting metric can be obtained from the\nmaximum of all maxima. To make a distinction in the\nnotation, we introduce the prefix “m” to the name of\nthe metric. If the SCLmax value of device k is named\nSCLmax,k , then, the mSCLmax metric is obtained as:\nmSCLmax = max {SCLmax,k }\n\n(3)\n\nNote that the mSCL estimation could use more\nelaborate ways of combining series of LAF values\nthan the simple formulation in equation (3), so that\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\n(b) Multi-unit system with a higher density of devices\n(K=16).\n\n(c) Three-unit system distributed over the pitch area.\nThis system can be combined with the system in panels (a) or (b), leading to a 9- or 19-device system, respectively.\n\nFigure 4: Schematic of three multi-unit systems for a stereotypical stadium with seating sections around the pitch. The microphone symbols indicate distributed measurement devices. Two\nrelevant target areas that could be related to singing and visitors’\nsections are highlighted in blue and red, respectively. Panels (a)\nand (b) represent two systems that are increasingly more accurate than the one-device systems from Figure 1. Although these\nsystems in panels (a) and (b) are still focused on the audience\narea only, they can be extended to cover the pitch if combined\nwith the system from panel (c).\n\nPage 9\n\n\fthat is assumed to be reliably covered by the corresponding device. The seating sections are coloured\nblue for the singing section, red for the visitors section, and grey for the remaining sections. The microphone symbols indicate the measurement device\nlocations.\nTwo simple one-device systems were introduced\nin Figure 1. Figure 1(a) reflects the current GWR\npractice, targeted at one specific audience area.\nThe system in Figure 4(a) represents a system\nwhere arbitrarily two devices on each side of the stadium are placed, with a total of K=8 devices. Under\nthis criterion, the schematic singing section is covered by two devices while the visitors section is still\nnot directly covered by any of the other 6 devices.\nWith the hypothesis that supporters from either the\nsinging or visitors’ sections can lead to the highest\ncrowd noise levels, this system will still provide more\nadvantage to the singing section. The visitors’ cheering will however be much better covered, due to two\ndevices that are close (but not close enough) to the\nvisitors’ area (in red).\nThe system in Figure 4(b) represents a system\nwith a fairer coverage of the whole stadium, where\nfour devices are used along each side, with a total\nof K=16 devices. In this case, the visitors will be\nmore accurately followed, giving them the possibility to drive the SCL estimate to them. Even if the visitors do not produce high levels, a comparison of the\nvisitors’ SCL and the SCL estimate for the singing\nsection can lead to an interesting estimate of the stadium atmosphere, particularly for actions led by the\nhome or the away team.\nIn order to extend the monitoring of crowd noises\nto other stadium locations, the systems in Figure 4\ncan be combined with one or more devices that cover\nthe pitch area, as schematically drawn in Figure 1(b)\nand Figure 4(c), respectively.\n4.3 Device installation\nOne of the challenges of a projection onto the pitch\nis related to the proper installation of devices that\nare sufficiently close to the pitch. If the stadium is\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\nopen there might not be any mounting point above\nthe pitch or the mounting possibilities may be very\nlimited. This is in contrast to indoor stadiums where\ndevices could be mounted on the roof or from trusses.\nAlternatives to ceiling installations [Figure 1(a)], are\nthe installation of microphones alongside the pitch\n[Figure 1(b)] or even the use of microphones as\nwearable devices, similar in concept to referee-view\nbroadcast systems in elite football [40]. Under such\ninstallation constraints, accurate projections of a stadium level will require a more elaborate processing\nalgorithm but, as pointed out earlier in this study, it\ncould be relevant to study and keep track of historic\nlevels projected to the field such that noise dosimetry\nestimates for players can be derived.\n5. Discussion and perspectives for the future\nIn the current study, we proposed a metric for the\ncomparison of stadiums such that the levels of the\ncrowd or “loudness” could be assessed. We presented a high-level description indicating relevant\nconsiderations related to the definition of the measurement locations and the acoustic metrics to be reported, such that future reports of crowd levels are\nbased on valid acoustic measurements in contrast to\nthe current records listed in Table 1.\n5.1 Main recommendations\nThe high-level description of the proposed measurement framework was focused on identifying weak\nchoices, often omitted, in the measurement protocols\nthat have been adopted in previous assessments of\ncrowd noise levels.\nFor a fair cross-venue comparison, spatially distributed measurements should be regarded as the recommended approach to estimate crowd noise levels.\nA single-anchor measurement may be useful as a\ntransparent minimum baseline, but it should not be\ninterpreted as equivalent to a spatially representative\nstadium assessment.\nMore generally, we defined (1) the minimum\ndistance that is required to ensure a far field mea-\n\nPage 10\n\n\fsurement, (2) the recommendation of using fastintegrated A-weighted sound pressure levels, and\n(3) the use of traceable instruments to collect the\ndata.\n5.2 Limitations and future work\n5.2.1 Other statistics instead of the maximum levels\nThe current SCL proposal is focused on estimations\nusing maximum levels. While this choice aligns with\nthe GWR procedure and improves it, it may still provide insufficient information for the appropriate characterisation of crowd noise at a stadium. As part of a\nrevised version of the current SCL proposal, the following aspects need to be addressed and refined:\n• Which specific level statistic is best suited to assess\neach individual anchor metric: next to the LAF,max\nlevels, LAeq values or other estimates may be more\ninformative. These extra options may be sport dependent or even sound-event dependent (see Section 3.2.3).\n• The combination of levels from multiple anchors\nusing maximum levels [Equation (3)] may not be\nsufficiently informative of, e.g., an overall maximum level as experienced by a player, or of the\nlevel contrasts between audience sections.\nThe test cases under which the current multi-unit\nestimation will be representative and when a more\nelaborate combination of crowd levels between units\nwill be required needs to be investigated.\n5.2.2 New test cases and crowd noise database\nDue to the high-level nature of the proposed method,\nno test cases are shared in this study. However, it\nis of crucial importance to have established an objective way of characterising crowd noise in stadiums first. The main motivation for this approach is\nthe complex nature and diversity of sound events that\ntake place during a sport event and the great variability that can be observed at different locations in the\nstadium. For an appropriate estimation of stadium\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\ncrowd noise, we also postulate that the players’ experience should be well captured, requiring to focus\non crowd noise as projected onto the pitch. In addition, considering that many modern stadiums are\nmultiuse and can even have retractable roofs [1], it\nmay be worth to treat multiuse stadiums as separate\nvenues for different sports.\nTo further advance the discussion of these aspects, we need to collect data and develop a database\nof sports venues with reliable estimates of crowd\nnoise.\n5.2.3 Account for the exact acoustic environment\nWe recommend to characterise a stadium based on\nfar-field measurements. For this recommendation we\nlinked the minimum distance for a reliable acoustic\nmeasurement to the lowest frequency of interest. Depending on the fulfilment of that criterion in addition\nto the use of multiple anchor devices, the measurement points and the audience can be very far apart.\nIn this case, a distance compensation algorithm may\nbe required. If this approach is needed, a physical\ncorrection that depends on distance [41, 42], temperature, relative humidity, or any other atmospheric or\ngeometrical factor may be required. These aspects\nwill be related to the type of acoustic field of the stadium ranging from open, semi-open, or close, and its\nspecific dimensions. A procedure to obtain a reliable\nsource-dependent transfer function may be needed in\nthe future.\n5.2.4 Possibility of real-time noise mapping\nAlthough we encouraged the use of multiple devices,\nwe did not emphasise the wide range of possibilities\noffered by the use of distributed microphone arrays,\nor acoustic cameras. In such a case, using the beamforming technique, local SCLmax values can be projected to a group of seats, obtaining a noise map with\na detailed grid. This is similar to the classical noise\nmaps in acoustics [43] but more granular because\neach projected point will have its own level trace as\na function of time. To convert such a map to a static\nmap, any acoustic metric could be applied, e.g., by\n\nPage 11\n\n\fkeeping the maximum obtained from each device, by\naveraging the LAF values, or by using other metrics\nsuch as percentiles applied to the time-varying estimates. These possibilities will be explored in future publications. Note that such noise maps can\nbe employed to complement SCLmax assessments in\nmany different ways, that include building a database\nof historic levels for one stadium or across stadiums\nor for investigating the crowd behaviour for specific\nmatch events (e.g., goals, free throws, or free kicks).\n5.3 Final remarks\nIn this study, we proposed a measurement framework for transparent and reproducible evaluation of\ncrowd noise during sport events. The framework\ndefines a representative stadium crowd level (SCL)\nas a spatially representative estimate of audiencegenerated A-weighted sound pressure levels, with\nspatially distributed measurement as the preferred\nroute for cross-venue comparison. A single-anchor\n(SCLmax ) metric is retained as a transparent minimum reporting baseline when distributed measurement is not feasible, but should not be interpreted\n\nas equivalent to a spatially representative stadium assessment. The method is focused on how to use an\nacoustic measurement device that should minimally\nhave one microphone, as is the case of the standard\nsound level meters, but it can actually use other devices.\nThe main purpose of the current study is to raise\nawareness of the potential technical flaws of previous crowd noise measurements, to overcome these\nissues in future reports targeted to either scientific or\ngeneral audiences. We also suggest that a fair crowd\nnoise estimate should not only be representative of\nthe levels in supporters’ areas but should also account\nfor the players’ experience on the pitch. We invite the\nscientific community to discuss, scrutinise, and further develop measurement guidelines, so that future\nstadium level reports meet all the minimum acoustic\nstandards. Such a synergy could also help to establish a procedure valid not only for mobile systems\n(point-based measurements) but also valid for installations of fixed systems to which an uncertainty can\nbe attributed. Such guidelines can help the future fair\ncomparison of crowd noise levels across stadiums.\n\n6. References\n[1] G. Siebein, K. Siebein, J. Wrightson, J. Solway, and R. Patel, “Large-venue acoustics: Arenas, stadiums, and amphitheaters,”\nAcoustics Today, vol. 20, pp. 55–65, 2024. https://doi.org/10.1121/AT.2024.20.1.55.\n[2] J. Oldfield, R. Oldfield, and D. Holmes, “The effects of different types of crowd noise on penalty taking performance in football,”\nInt. J. Sport Exerc. Psychol., vol. 24, pp. 67–84, 2026. https://doi.org/10.1080/1612197X.2024.2432996.\n[3] J. Taylor, S. Mellalieu, N. James, and D. Shearer, “The influence of match location, quality of opposition, and match status on\ntechnical performance in professional association football,” Journal of Sports Sciences, vol. 26, pp. 885–895, 2008. https:\n//doi.org/10.1080/02640410701836887.\n[4] A. Barnard, S. Porter, J. Bostron, R. terMeulen, and S. Hambric, “Evaluation of crowd noise levels during college football games,”\nNoise Control Eng. J., vol. 59, pp. 667–680, 2011. https://doi.org/10.3397/1.3654144.\n[5] C. Unkelbach and D. Memmert, “Crowd noise as a cue in referee decisions contributes to the home advantage,” J. Sport Exerc.\nPsychol., vol. 32, pp. 483–498, 2010. https://doi.org/10.1123/jsep.32.4.483.\n[6] Guinness World Records, “Loudest crowd roar at a sports stadium,” 2014. www.guinnessworldrecords.com/worldrecords/loudest-crowd-roar-at-a-sports-stadium (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[7] Guinness World Records, “Seattle Seahawks fans cause minor earthquake with world record crowd roar,” 2013.\nwww.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/12/seattle-seahawks-fans-cause-minor-earthquakewith-world-record-crowd-roar-53285 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[8] Chiefs, “Records were broken today at Arrowhead Stadium!,” 2013. www.chiefs.com/news/records-broken11499403 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\nPage 12\n\n\f[9] Saturday Down South, “Tennessee breaks decibel record as Neyland stadium roars against Georgia,” 2023.\nwww.saturdaydownsouth.com/news/college-football/tennessee-breaks-decibel-record-asneyland-stadium-roars-against-georgia/ (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[10] Guinness World Records,\n“Seattle Seahawks break record for loudest stadium crowd roar,”\n2013.\nwww.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/9/seattle-seahawks-break-record-for-loudeststadium-crowd-roar-51331 (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[11] The Seattle Times, “How UW won perhaps the loudest college football game ever played 30 years ago against\nNebraska,” 2022. www.seattletimes.com/sports/washington-huskies-football/how-uw-won-perhapsthe-loudest-college-football-game-ever-played (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[12] Everton FC, “Top 5 loudest recorded crowd noises in football stadiums,” 2025. Facebook post, www.facebook.com/\nEvertonOnceABlueAlwaysABlue/posts/top-5-loudest-recorded-crowd-noises-ever-infootball-stadiums1-besiktass-vodafon/1367726645354829/ (Accessed: 23 June 2026).\n[13] Guinness World Records, “Galatasaray—Loudest crowd roar at a sport stadium:\nwww.youtube.com/watch?v=H96QXhrE1Bw (Accessed: 16 July 2026).\n\n131.76 dB,” 2011. https://\n\n[14] Guinness World Records, “Loudest crowd roar at an indoor sports event,” 2017. www.guinnessworldrecords.com/worldrecords/loudest-crowd-roar-at-a-sports-stadium-(indoors) (Accessed 23 June 2026).\n[15] Knoxville News Sentinel, “How loud was Neyland stadium when Tennessee football beat Alabama? was it dangerous?,” 2022.\nhttps://eu.knoxnews.com/story/sports/college/university-of-tennessee/football/2022/10/\n19/tennessee-football-fans-neyland-stadium-noise-decibels-alabama/69573565007/ (Accessed:\n1 June 2026).\n[16] Acentech, “Making some noise: We’re questioning those world record stadium sound levels.” www.acentech.com/\nresources/making-some-noise-were-questioning-those-world-record-stadium-sound-levels/,\n2019. (Accessed: 1 June 2026).\n[17] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 1996-1:2016 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of\nenvironmental noise – Part 1: Basic quantities and assessment procedures,” 2016. https://www.iso.org/standard/\n59765.html.\n[18] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 1996-2:2017 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of environmental noise – Part 2: Determination of sound pressure levels,” 2017. https://www.iso.org/standard/59766.html.\n[19] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO/PAS 1996-3:2022 Acoustics – Description, measurement and assessment of\nenvironmental noise – Part 3: Objective method for the measurement of prominence of impulsive sounds and for adjustment of\nLAeq,” 2022. https://www.iso.org/standard/77035.html.\n[20] A. Barnard, “A proposed technique for measuring and comparing crowd noise from sporting events,” in Inter-Noise\n2015, pp. 366–373, 2015. https://ince.publisher.ingentaconnect.com/content/ince/incecp/2015/\n00000250/00000007/art00037.\n[21] W. Van Ransbeeck, N. De Poortere, M. Kok, and S. Verhulst, “Characteristics of personal sound and noise exposure at large-scale\nmusic events,” J. Audio Eng. Soc., vol. 72, pp. 901–912, 2024. https://doi.org/10.17743/jaes.2022.0184.\n[22] International Organization for Standardization, “ISO 9612:2025 Acoustics — Determination of occupational noise exposure —\nMethodology,” 2025.\n[23] E. Zwicker, G. Flottorp, and S. Stevens, “Critical band width in loudness summation,” J. Acoust. Soc. Am., vol. 29, pp. 548–557,\n1957. https://doi.org/10.1121/1.1908963.\n[24] A. Osses, G. Felix Greco, and R. Merino-Martı́nez, “Considerations for the perceptual evaluation of steady-state and timevarying sounds using psychoacoustic metrics,” in Forum Acusticum, (Torino, Italy), pp. 6319–6326, 2023. https://doi.org/\n10.61782/fa.2023.0600.\n[25] B. Moore, An Introduction to the Psychology of Hearing. Leiden, The Netherlands: Brill, 6 ed., 2013.\n[26] D. Houser, W. Yost, R. Burkard, J. Finneran, C. Reichmuth, and J. Mulsow, “A review of the history, development and application\nof auditory weighting functions in humans and marine mammals,” J. Acoust. Soc. Am., vol. 141, pp. 1371–1413, 2017. https:\n//doi.org/10.1121/1.4976086.\n\nAuthor manuscript: Osses et al. / July 22, 2026\n\nPage 13\n\n\f", "numLines": 917, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 917}}}
